<DocsLayout title="Resizable columns — react-data-table-component">
  <h1>Resizable columns</h1>

  <p>
    Enable drag-to-resize handles on column headers by setting <code>resizable</code>.
    Users can drag the right edge of any header cell to adjust its width.
  </p>

  <h2>Basic usage</h2>

  <pre><code>{`<DataTable columns={columns} data={data} resizable />`}</code></pre>

  <p>All columns become resizable by default when <code>resizable</code> is set.</p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>

  <p>
    Column widths are tracked in component state as pixel values. When the user starts
    dragging, a <code>mousemove</code> listener computes the delta from the drag start point
    and sets the new width (minimum 40 px). No layout thrashing occurs — widths are applied
    as inline styles only on the affected column.
  </p>

  <h2>Combining with fixed widths</h2>

  <p>
    A column with an explicit <code>width</code> prop will start at that width and remain
    resizable from there. A column with <code>minWidth</code> will not shrink below it.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{`const columns = [
  { name: 'Name',   selector: r => r.name,   width: '200px', minWidth: '120px' },
  { name: 'Status', selector: r => r.status, width: '100px' },
];

<DataTable columns={columns} data={data} resizable />`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Persisting widths</h2>

  <p>
    Column widths are in-memory only — they reset on remount. To persist them,
    save to <code>localStorage</code> on resize:
  </p>

  <pre><code>{`// Not a built-in prop yet — implement via onColumnOrderChange and
// a wrapper that intercepts resize events if you need persistence.`}</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
